"name":"Gobert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Antoine, Marie-France, Monique.","French, German, and English (London): from a medieval personal name, <i>Godebert</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was popularized in England by the Normans, and probably absorbed an Old English form <i>Godbeorht</i>."]},{"name":"Goben","meanings":["Altered form of   Gobin  , a surname of English or French origin. In some cases however, the surname <i>Goben</i> (possibly of German origin; see 2 below) was changed to <i>Gobin</i>.","German (<b>Göben</b>): habitational name from Gobbin on Rügen Island (Pomerania) or perhaps from any of several places called Goben in Bavaria."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Gobion was born in 1295, in Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England, her father, Sir Hugh Gobion IV of Shilvington, was 46 and her mother, Joan Morrel, was 46. She married Robert de Ogle about 1314, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1314, in Northumberland, England, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1295–1314":"1295–1314","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1295–1350":"1295–1350","1306–1362":"1306–1362","1312–1355":"1312–1355","1250–1317":"1250–1317","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","Abt 1314":"umbes 1314","1362":"1362","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","1355":"1355","about 1312":"umbes 1312","1306":"1306","1317":"1317","Ogle, Northumberlan